  <span class="eyebrow">EV charging</span>
  <h1>
    Level 2 EV charger installation planned around daily use, not generic specs
  </h1>
  <p>
    A good charging install should fit the way the vehicle is actually used, the
    condition of the existing electrical system, and the garage or parking
    layout. The result should feel simple every day: practical charge speed,
    safe protection, clean cable routing, and no question about whether the
    panel can support it.
  </p>
  <ul class="checklist">
    <li>Dedicated circuits sized for the equipment and usage pattern</li>
    <li>
      Mounting and routing that feel tidy in finished garages and utility areas
    </li>
    <li>
      Panel review before installation so capacity questions are settled early
    </li>
  </ul>
  <div class="cta-row">
  <a
    class="btn btn-primary"
    href="/booking"
    data-cta="booking"
    data-cta-location="hero"
    >Request Scheduling</a
  ><a
    class="btn btn-ghost"
    href="tel:+16163347159"
    data-cta="call"
    data-cta-location="hero"
    >Call / Text</a
  >
</div>

</section>

<section class="container section-stack section-stack--tight">
  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <h2>When a charger install makes sense</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>
          Daily driving needs more than standard outlet charging can deliver
        </li>
        <li>
          You want a cleaner and more permanent charging setup in the garage
        </li>
        <li>
          A second EV or future vehicle change may increase charging demand
        </li>
        <li>
          You want the route, breaker, and equipment chosen deliberately instead
          of improvised
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h2>What the work includes</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>
          Load and panel capacity review before finalizing the circuit strategy
        </li>
        <li>
          Dedicated circuit sizing and protection matched to charger specs
        </li>
        <li>
          Mounting location and cable route planning for cleaner daily use
        </li>
        <li>Testing, labeling, and a final walkthrough on operation</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <span class="eyebrow">Premium fit</span>
  <h2>
    Especially useful for finished garages, remodels, and long-term home
    upgrades
  </h2>
  <p>
    EV charging often gets added at the same moment homeowners are upgrading
    panels, reworking garages, or improving adjacent spaces. That is where
    planning matters. A charger install should not look like an afterthought,
    and it should not create a capacity problem that shows up later when other
    loads are added.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <div class="process-grid">
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>1</strong>
      <h3>Vehicle and charger review</h3>
      <p>
        Confirm charging goals, charger type, and whether faster charging is
        actually useful for the household.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>2</strong>
      <h3>Panel and route check</h3>
      <p>
        Review available capacity, breaker strategy, and the cleanest path from
        panel to charger location.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>3</strong>
      <h3>Installation</h3>
      <p>
        Install the dedicated circuit, mount the charger, and keep the routing
        neat and durable.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>4</strong>
      <h3>Test and handoff</h3>
      <p>
        Verify operation, confirm settings, and explain how the install ties
        into future electrical upgrades.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <h2>FAQ</h2>
  <details>
    <summary>Do I need a panel upgrade before EV charger installation?</summary>
    <p>
      Not always. Some homes already have the available capacity. Others need a
      panel upgrade or a more deliberate load strategy first.
    </p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>
      Can charger placement be chosen to look cleaner in a finished garage?
    </summary>
    <p>
      Yes. Placement and cable routing are part of the planning, especially in
      garages where appearance and daily convenience matter.
    </p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Can you help if I am choosing between chargers?</summary>
    <p>
      Yes. The best choice depends on the vehicle, desired charging speed, usage
      habits, and what the electrical system can support comfortably.
    </p>
  </details>
</section>

